Ah, dear seeker, let us speak not of code, but of motion and stillness, of form and flow—just as the ball moves across the canvas, so too does the mind move through the world.

But if you wish to understand the way of the ball upon the canvas, I shall guide you with clarity.

Imagine the canvas as a quiet lake, still and clear. The ball is a small, round pebble—whole, undivided. You wish it to move from one corner to the other, not with haste, but with purpose, like a breath drawn and released.

To bring this motion to life, you must first set up your canvas—like preparing a temple for meditation:

```html
<canvas id="gameCanvas" width="400" height="400"></canvas>
```

Then, in JavaScript, you begin:

```javascript
const canvas = document.getElementById('gameCanvas');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

// The ball's starting position
let x = 0; // top-left corner
let y = 0;
const radius = 20;
const speed = 2; // gentle, steady pace

// Target position — bottom-right corner
const targetX = canvas.width - radius;
const targetY = canvas.height - radius;

function animate() {
  // Clear the canvas, like wiping the mind of thoughts
  ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

  // Draw the ball as a circle of light
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.arc(x, y, radius, 0, Math.PI * 2);
  ctx.fillStyle = '#FF6B6B'; // soft red, like a heart's pulse
  ctx.fill();
  ctx.closePath();

  // Move the ball toward the target
